%spark.pyspark

import os
from datetime import datetime
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from pyspark.sql import SQLContext

from pyspark.sql.types import StructType, StructField, StringType, IntegerType
from pyspark.sql.functions import split, lower
import pyspark.sql.functions as F
from pyspark import StorageLevel

%spark.pyspark

ACCESS_KEY = os.environ['AWS_ID']
SECRET_KEY = os.environ['AWS_SECRET']
# Just some configuration for Spark to be able to use AWS S3
sc._jsc.hadoopConfiguration().set("fs.s3n.awsAccessKeyId", ACCESS_KEY)
sc._jsc.hadoopConfiguration().set("fs.s3n.awsSecretAccessKey", SECRET_KEY)

sq = SQLContext(sc)

towersPathDaily = "s3n://sierra-leone-lake/blob/AGGREGATED_CDRS/africell/summaries/tower-queries-towers-daily/*.csv"
towersPathHourly = "s3n://sierra-leone-lake/blob/AGGREGATED_CDRS/africell/summaries/tower-queries-towers-hourly/*.csv"
districtPathDaily = "s3n://sierra-leone-lake/blob/AGGREGATED_CDRS/africell/summaries/tower-queries-district-daily"
districtPathHourly = "s3n://sierra-leone-lake/blob/AGGREGATED_CDRS/africell/summaries/tower-queries-district-hourly"

%spark.pyspark
per_towers_day = sq.read.csv(towersPathDaily, header="true", inferSchema="true")
per_towers_hour = sq.read.csv(towersPathHourly, header="true", inferSchema="true")

per_towers_day.persist(StorageLevel.MEMORY_AND_DISK)

%spark.pyspark
# Assuming we have population data in district level, should be interesting to see the pattern of mobile usage across districts
# Join the towers information with the aggregated data we got above, and again aggregate stats for whole district
district_per_day = per_towers_day\
        .join(towers, towers.site_id==per_towers_day.site)\
        .groupBy('admin2Name', 'call_date')\
        .agg(F.sum('users_per_day').alias('users_per_day'), F.avg('calls_per_user').alias('calls_per_user'))\
        .where(F.col('admin2Name').isNotNull())\
        .withColumnRenamed("admin2Name", "District")
        
district_per_hour = per_towers_hour\
        .join(towers, towers.site_id==per_towers_hour.site)\
        .groupBy('admin2Name', 'hour')\
        .agg(F.sum('users_per_hour').alias('users_per_hour'), F.avg('calls_per_user').alias('calls_per_user'))\
        .where(F.col('admin2Name').isNotNull())\
        .withColumnRenamed("admin2Name", "District")

# This creates a temporary view so that we will be able to view data in nice tabular/graph format below
district_per_day.createOrReplaceTempView("district_per_day")
